label: Engineer
description: Professional engineer responsible for providing engineering services, designing systems, and ensuring public safety through technical expertise
text_references: As members of this profession, engineers are expected to exhibit the highest standards of honesty and integrity
Engineers, in the fulfillment of their professional duties, shall:
Engineers shall hold paramount the safety, health, and welfare of the public

label: Employer
description: Organization or individual that employs engineers and receives their professional services
text_references: Act for each employer or client as faithful agents or trustees
Notify employer or client and appropriate authority if judgment is overruled
Do not disclose client/employer information without consent

label: Client
description: Individual or organization that contracts with engineers for professional services
text_references: Act for each employer or client as faithful agents or trustees
Notify employer or client and appropriate authority if judgment is overruled
Do not disclose client/employer information without consent

label: Public
description: General population whose safety, health, and welfare are affected by engineering work
text_references: Hold paramount the safety, health, and welfare of the public
Engineers shall hold paramount the safety, health, and welfare of the public
Engineers shall strive to serve the public interest

label: Sales Engineer
description: Engineer who works in sales capacity and makes professional product comparisons
text_references: Sales engineers may make professional product comparisons

label: NSPE Code of Ethics
description: National Society of Professional Engineers' comprehensive code of ethical conduct containing fundamental canons, rules of practice, and professional obligations for engineers

label: Engineering Standards
description: Technical standards and specifications that engineering documents must conform to for approval

label: Professional Registration Laws
description: Legal requirements and regulations governing professional engineering licensure and practice

label: Professional or Public Bodies
description: Regulatory and professional organizations responsible for receiving reports of code violations and maintaining professional standards

label: Appropriate Authority
description: Designated officials or organizations that must be notified when engineering judgments are overruled in ways that endanger life or property

label: Public Safety and Welfare
description: Engineers must hold paramount the safety, health, and welfare of the public in all professional activities

label: Honesty and Integrity
description: Engineers must exhibit the highest standards of honesty and integrity in all professional conduct

label: Competence
description: Engineers shall perform services only in areas of their professional competence and expertise

label: Truthfulness and Objectivity
description: Engineers must issue public statements and provide testimony in an objective and truthful manner based on facts

label: Fiduciary Duty
description: Engineers shall act as faithful agents or trustees for each employer or client

label: Avoidance of Deception
description: Engineers must avoid deceptive acts and conduct that deceives the public

label: Confidentiality
description: Engineers must maintain confidentiality of client and employer information without proper consent or legal obligation

label: Conflict of Interest Avoidance
description: Engineers must avoid and disclose conflicts of interest and not be influenced by conflicting interests

label: Professional Responsibility
description: Engineers shall accept responsibility for their actions and conduct themselves to enhance the profession's honor and reputation

label: Fairness and Equity
description: Engineers must provide services with fairness, equity, and impartiality, treating all individuals with fairness and respect

label: Public Interest Service
description: Engineers should strive to serve the public interest through civic engagement, education, and promoting understanding of engineering

label: Professional Credit and Recognition
description: Engineers must appropriately credit others for their work and not harm others' professional reputation

label: Hold paramount public safety, health, and welfare
description: Engineers must prioritize the safety, health, and welfare of the public above all other considerations in their professional duties

label: Perform services only within competence
description: Engineers shall only undertake work in areas where they possess adequate knowledge, training, and experience

label: Issue objective and truthful public statements
description: Engineers must provide factual, unbiased information in all public communications and testimony

label: Act as faithful agents or trustees
description: Engineers must serve employers and clients with loyalty, avoiding conflicts of interest and maintaining fiduciary responsibilities

label: Avoid deceptive acts
description: Engineers must not engage in misrepresentation, bribery, or other fraudulent practices

label: Conduct themselves honorably and ethically
description: Engineers must maintain high standards of professional behavior to enhance the profession's reputation

label: Maintain honesty and integrity
description: Engineers must admit errors, correct mistakes, and deal truthfully in all professional matters

label: Serve the public interest
description: Engineers should engage in civic activities, promote public understanding of engineering, and support sustainability

label: Maintain confidentiality
description: Engineers must protect confidential information of clients and employers without proper consent or legal obligation

label: Avoid conflicting interests
description: Engineers must reject improper inducements and avoid situations that compromise professional judgment

label: Not seek gain through improper means
description: Engineers must avoid unethical fee arrangements and misuse of employer resources for personal benefit

label: Not harm others' professional reputation
description: Engineers must not unfairly damage the professional standing of colleagues without proper disclosure

label: Accept responsibility for actions
description: Engineers must follow registration laws and cannot hide behind corporate structures to avoid ethical accountability

label: Credit others appropriately
description: Engineers must acknowledge contributions of others and respect proprietary rights in professional work

label: Judgment overruled
description: When an engineer's professional judgment is overruled in a way that endangers life or property

label: Code violation discovery
description: When engineers become aware of violations of codes, standards, or regulations

label: Conflict of interest discovery
description: When actual or potential conflicts of interest are identified

label: Error occurrence
description: When mistakes or errors are made in engineering work

label: Project issues
description: When problems or complications arise in engineering projects

label: Pressure to sign non-compliant documents
description: When engineers face pressure to approve documents that don't meet standards

label: Gift or consideration offer
description: When engineers are offered gifts, bribes, or other considerations from outside parties

label: Outside work opportunity
description: When engineers are presented with work opportunities outside their primary employment

label: Request for confidential information
description: When there are requests or pressures to disclose confidential client or employer information

label: Fraudulent enterprise association
description: When engineers encounter opportunities to associate with fraudulent or dishonest enterprises

label: Unlawful practice request
description: When engineers are asked to aid or participate in unlawful engineering practices

label: Competence boundary exceeded
description: When engineers are asked to work outside their areas of expertise or competence

label: Professional competence
description: Ability to perform services only in areas of expertise and qualification

label: Technical expertise
description: Specialized knowledge in specific engineering domains

label: Ethical judgment
description: Ability to make decisions based on highest principles of ethical conduct

label: Honesty
description: Capability to exhibit truthfulness and integrity in professional conduct

label: Integrity
description: Ability to maintain moral uprightness and adherence to ethical principles

label: Objectivity
description: Capability to issue statements and make decisions in an impartial manner

label: Communication skills
description: Ability to issue public statements in truthful and objective manner

label: Problem-solving
description: Cognitive ability to address engineering challenges and project issues

label: Professional responsibility
description: Capability to accept and fulfill professional duties and obligations

label: Confidentiality management
description: Ability to maintain and protect confidential information appropriately

label: Conflict identification
description: Capability to recognize and disclose conflicts of interest

label: Quality assurance
description: Ability to approve only engineering documents that conform to standards

label: Professional development
description: Commitment to ongoing learning and skill enhancement

label: Public safety awareness
description: Capability to prioritize public health, safety, and welfare

label: Truthful representation
description: Ability to accurately represent qualifications and work without deception

label: Public safety endangerment
description: Condition where engineering judgment being overruled could endanger life or property

label: Outside area of competence
description: Situation where an engineer lacks the necessary expertise or qualifications for a particular assignment or decision

label: Conflict of interest
description: Situation where personal, financial, or other interests may compromise professional judgment or loyalty to employer/client

label: Confidential information disclosure
description: State involving access to or potential sharing of client/employer confidential or proprietary information

label: Code violation knowledge
description: Condition where an engineer becomes aware of violations of applicable codes, standards, or regulations

label: Multiple compensation arrangement
description: Situation where an engineer receives or may receive compensation from multiple parties for the same work or related services

label: Public decision-making role
description: Condition where an engineer serves in a governmental or public capacity that involves decision-making affecting their private interests

label: Specialized knowledge from previous employment
description: State where an engineer possesses confidential or proprietary knowledge from former employer that could create conflicts in new employment
